  "A pharmaceutical company tests a new blood pressure medication. The treatment group (n = 150) has a mean reduction of 12 mmHg with s = 8, while the placebo group (n = 150) has a mean reduction of 4 mmHg with s = 7. What is the estimated difference in mean reduction and which procedure should be used?": "",
  "Difference = 16 mmHg; use a chi-square test": "",
  "Difference = 8 mmHg; use a two-sample t-test for means": "",
  "Difference = 8 mmHg; use a paired t-test": "",
  "Difference = 4 mmHg; use a one-sample t-test": "",
  "Difference = 12 − 4 = 8 mmHg. Two independent groups with quantitative outcomes require a two-sample t-test. A paired test would only apply if the same subjects were in both groups.": "",
  "An e-commerce company runs an A/B test: Page A shows 320 purchases out of 4,000 visitors (8%), while Page B shows 380 purchases out of 4,000 visitors (9.5%). The two-proportion z-test yields z = 2.35 and p = 0.019. At α = 0.05, what should the company conclude?": "",
  "The test is invalid because the sample sizes are too large": "",
  "There is statistically significant evidence that Page B has a higher conversion rate than Page A": "",
  "There is no significant difference between the two pages": "",
  "Page A is better because 8% is a high conversion rate": "",
  "Since p = 0.019 < 0.05, we reject H₀ and conclude there is convincing evidence that Page B's conversion rate (9.5%) is significantly higher than Page A's (8%).": "",
  "A sports analyst computes that a basketball player's true shooting percentage is 58.2% while the league average is 55.0%. The analyst constructs a 95% CI of (56.1%, 60.3%) for the player's true shooting percentage. What can the analyst conclude?": "",
  "The confidence interval proves causation between the player shooting mechanics and performance": "",
  "The player is definitely the best shooter in the league based on this single confidence interval": "",
  "The player true shooting percentage could be below the league average based on this interval": "",
  "Since the entire 95% CI (56.1% to 60.3%) is above the league average of 55.0%, there is convincing evidence the player's true shooting percentage exceeds the league average": "",
  "Because the entire interval lies above 55.0%, we can be confident the player's true shooting percentage is above the league average.": "",
  "An economist uses regression to model the relationship between years of education (x) and annual income (y, in thousands). The model yields ŷ = 15.2 + 5.8x with r² = 0.42. What does this mean in context?": "",
  "Each additional year of education causes income to increase by exactly 5800 dollars for everyone": "",
  "42% of people earn more with more education, while the remaining 58% see no income benefit": "",
  "Income is always 15200 dollars when education is zero because that is the intercept of the model": "",
  "For each additional year of education, the predicted annual income increases by $5,800 on average, and 42% of the variation in income is explained by years of education": "",
  "The slope (5.8) means each additional year of education is associated with a $5,800 increase in predicted income. r² = 0.42 means education explains 42% of income variability. Causation is not implied by regression alone.": "",
  "A quality control engineer monitors a production line using a control chart. The process mean is 50.0 g and the control limits are set at 50.0 ± 3(0.5) = (48.5, 51.5). If a sample mean comes in at 52.1 g, what should the engineer do?": "",
  "Widen the control limits to include the value of 52.1 so that the process appears stable again": "",
  "Ignore it because it is close to the upper limit and minor variations are expected in any process": "",
  "Immediately shut down the entire factory and cease all production until a full audit is completed": "",
  "Investigate the process because the sample mean (52.1) exceeds the upper control limit (51.5), signaling the process may be out of control": "",
  "52.1 > 51.5 (the UCL), so the point falls outside the control limits. This triggers an investigation to find and correct the assignable cause.": "",
  "A medical study reports a relative risk (RR) of 2.5 for lung cancer among smokers compared to non-smokers. What does this mean?": "",
  "25% of smokers will develop lung cancer": "",
  "Non-smokers have a 2.5% chance of lung cancer": "",
  "Smokers are 2.5 percentage points more likely to develop lung cancer": "",
  "Smokers are 2.5 times as likely to develop lung cancer compared to non-smokers": "",
  "RR = 2.5 means the exposed group (smokers) has 2.5 times the risk of developing lung cancer compared to the unexposed group (non-smokers).": "",
  "A sports team's data analyst finds that a pitcher's expected ERA based on advanced metrics (FIP) is 3.20, but his actual ERA is 4.50. The analyst reports that the 95% CI for his true ERA based on FIP is (2.80, 3.60). What insight does this provide?": "",
  "The pitcher should be released immediately because his actual ERA exceeds the advanced metric prediction": "",
  "The pitcher's actual ERA (4.50) is well above the CI for his expected performance, suggesting he has been unlucky or factors outside his control (like defense) inflated his ERA": "",
  "FIP is an unreliable metric that cannot be used to evaluate pitcher performance with any confidence": "",
  "The pitcher is permanently bad and will never perform at the level predicted by his underlying stats": "",
  "When actual performance falls well outside the CI of expected performance, external factors (luck, defense, sequencing) likely explain the gap, suggesting regression toward the expected level.": "",
  "An epidemiologist tracks weekly flu cases and notices that the current week's count (450) is more than 2 standard deviations above the seasonal baseline mean of 300 (SD = 60). What does this signal?": "",
  "The standard deviation should be recalculated using a larger historical dataset for greater precision": "",
  "The flu season is ending naturally, and the current spike is just a temporary fluctuation in cases": "",
  "The count (450) exceeds the baseline by more than 2 SDs (threshold = 300 + 2(60) = 420), indicating a potential outbreak that warrants investigation": "",
  "Everything is normal because flu case counts always vary from week to week during the typical season": "",
  "450 > 420 (the 2-SD threshold), flagging the week as statistically unusual. This is the basis of statistical surveillance for outbreak detection.": "",
  "A clinical trial for a new cancer drug reports a hazard ratio (HR) of 0.70 with a 95% CI of (0.55, 0.90) for the treatment group compared to the control. What does this mean?": "",
  "The treatment reduced the hazard of death by approximately 30% compared to control, and the CI excludes 1.0, indicating statistical significance": "",
  "There is no difference between treatment and control": "",
  "70% of patients survived in the treatment group": "",
  "The treatment group had a 70% higher risk of death": "",
  "HR = 0.70 means the treatment group has 70% the hazard (risk) of the control, or a 30% reduction. Since the CI (0.55, 0.90) does not include 1.0, the result is statistically significant.": "",
  "An economist models housing prices using multiple regression: Price = 50,000 + 120(sqft) + 15,000(bedrooms) − 2,000(age). A house has 1,500 sqft, 3 bedrooms, and is 20 years old. What is the predicted price?": "",
